LC 44 3208S
The House Committee on Rules offers the following substitute to HR 753:
A RESOLUTION
1 SECTION 1.
2 Creating the House Study Committee on Improving Access to Internal Medicine in
3 Underserved Areas; and for other purposes.
4 WHEREAS, 75 percent of Georgia counties are considered rural; and
5 WHEREAS, rural Georgian communities often lack access to quality health care; and
6 WHEREAS, as of 2022, one in ten Georgians live in a county with no more than a single
7 physician; and
8 WHEREAS, recent studies have reported that approximately 40 counties, making up roughly
9 one-quarter of Georgia's total county count, have no internal medicine physician; and
10 WHEREAS, Georgia ranked fortieth among all states in the ratio of active patient care
11 physicians to the population, with one physician for every 480 people; and
12 WHEREAS, as of last year, 142 of Georgia's 159 counties are healthcare professional
13 shortage areas, meaning there are 3,500 or more patients for every one provider; and
- 1 -

LC 44 3208S
14 WHEREAS, rural communities within the state are challenged with recruiting and retaining
15 healthcare providers and staff; and
16 WHEREAS, transportation is not always accessible in rural areas of the state; and
17 WHEREAS, three out of four counties in Georgia are considered health transportation
18 shortage areas; and
19 WHEREAS, health transportation shortage areas experience increased levels of
20 transportation barriers to healthcare, such as public transportation availability and high
21 household poverty rates; and
22 WHEREAS, a study committee is needed to thoroughly evaluate the most prudent and
23 cost-effective ways to increase access to internal medicine in rural Georgian communities,
24 with particular focus on those rural communities experiencing health transportation
25 shortages.
26 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES:
27 (1) Creation of House study committee. There is created the House Study Committee
28 on Improving Access to Internal Medicine in Underserved Areas.
29 (2) Members and officers.
30 (A) The committee shall be composed of eight members.
31 (B) The Speaker of the House of Representatives shall appoint five members of the
32 House of Representatives.
33 (C) The Speaker shall also appoint an additional three nonlegislative members of the
34 committee who are licensed healthcare providers in this state and who are familiar with
35 the needs of rural Georgia.
- 2 -

LC 44 3208S
36 (D) The Speaker shall also designate a legislative member of the committee as
37 chairperson of the committee.
38 (3) Powers and duties. The committee shall undertake a study of the conditions, needs,
39 issues, and problems mentioned above or related thereto and recommend any action or
40 legislation which the committee deems necessary or appropriate.
41 (4) Meetings. The chairperson shall call all meetings of the committee. The committee
42 may conduct such meetings at such places and at such times as it may deem necessary or
43 convenient to enable it to exercise fully and effectively its powers, perform its duties, and
44 accomplish the objectives and purposes of this resolution.
45 (5) Allowances, expenses, and funding.
46 (A) The legislative members of the committee shall receive the allowances provided
47 for in Code Section 28-1-8 of the Official Code of Georgia Annotated.
48 (B) Members of the committee who are not legislators, state officials, or state
49 employees shall receive a daily expense allowance in an amount the same as that
50 specified in subsection (b) of Code Section 45-7-21 of the Official Code of Georgia
51 Annotated, as well as the mileage or transportation allowance authorized for state
52 employees.
53 (C) The allowances authorized by this resolution shall not be received by any member
54 of the committee for more than three days unless additional days are authorized. Funds
55 necessary to carry out the provisions of this resolution shall come from funds
56 appropriated to the House of Representatives.
57 (6) Report.
58 (A) In the event the committee adopts any specific findings or recommendations that
59 include suggestions for proposed legislation, the chairperson shall file a report of the
60 same prior to the date of abolishment specified in this resolution, subject to
61 subparagraph (C) of this paragraph.
- 3 -

