122 SECTION 3.
123 Creating the House Study Committee on Gaming in the State of Georgia; and for other
124 purposes.
125 WHEREAS, the Georgia General Assembly has long considered multiple legislative
126 measures to permit the voters of Georgia to decide whether or not to allow the state and its
127 counties to decide whether or not to authorize or opt in to land based destination resort
128 casinos, pari-mutuel and fixed-odds horse racing, and whether or not to permit digital, retail,
129 and on-premise sports betting; and
130 WHEREAS, the General Assembly needs to determine how legalization of gaming in this
131 state if approved by the people and enabled by the General Assembly would contribute to the
132 economy and workforce development of this state as to revenue expectations and quality of
- 6 -

LC 44 3208S
133 jobs being available when weighed against what social and societal ills may come to Georgia
134 if gaming is approved by the citizens of this state; and
135 WHEREAS, the General Assembly needs to determine if the legalization of gaming would
136 also increase tax revenues for Georgia and aid in meeting the budgetary demands of
137 government; and
138 WHEREAS, many of our citizens travel substantial distances to engage in gaming activities
139 and enjoy the resort atmosphere in states such as Nevada, Mississippi, Alabama, North
140 Carolina, and Massachusetts; and
141 WHEREAS, if gaming was expanded in this state, the money spent in other states might
142 remain with the industries and tax revenues of this state; and
143 WHEREAS, the State of Georgia has a large agricultural industry that contributes
144 significantly to the economy of this state and a portion of that industry is involved with the
145 breeding, raising, and training of horses; and
146 WHEREAS, the legalization of horse racing and pari-mutuel betting in this state could aid
147 in the further development and expansion of Georgia's horse breeding and raising industry
148 and foster its contribution to the economy of this state; and
149 WHEREAS, the financial implications for the state of such potential legalization as well as
150 previously considered measures by the General Assembly to improve Georgia's economy
151 deserve to be further considered and studied along with the social, fiscal, and economic
152 impacts and the financial viability of such endeavors.
- 7 -

